{"type":"message","id":"d95461b2","parentId":"ed9bb522","timestamp":"2026-04-04T15:21:39.338Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `import.meta.url` when bundled is pointing to the dist folder's `lancedb-runtime-D3SpJhn5.js`, so `new URL(\"./package.json\", import.meta.url)` is trying to read `dist/package.json`, not `extensions/memory-lancedb/package.json`.\n\nThat's the bug! It's looking for the package.json in the wrong location. This is an OpenClaw bug - it's looking for the package.json relative to the bundled runtime file in dist/, not relative to the plugin folder.\n\nI created a symlink earlier to point `dist/package.json` to the main openclaw package.json, which doesn't have @lancedb/lancedb.\n\nThe fix is to create a package.json in the dist/ folder with the @lancedb/lancedb dependency, or update the symlink. Actually, the real issue is that the plugin code expects its own package.json to be in the same folder as the runtime, but it's not.\n\nActually I think I understand now. The bundled runtime is trying to find package.json in the same directory as itself (dist/), but it should be looking in the plugin directory. This is a bug in how the plugin is bundled.\n\nThe workaround would be to either:\n1. Add @lancedb/lancedb to the main dist/package.json (wrong, pollutes main package)\n2. Create a separate package.json in dist/ with just the dependency\n3. Fix the plugin code (not possible without modifying OpenClaw source)\n\nLet me try option 2 - create a package.json in dist/ with the lancedb dependency.\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_e86fbbee463d4f9ba277b403","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat > ~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/package.json << 'EOF'\n{\n  \"name\": \"openclaw\",\n  \"version\": \"2026.3.28\",\n  \"dependencies\": {\n    \"@lancedb/lancedb\": \"^0.27.2\"\n  }\n}\nEOF\necho \"Created dist/pac